travel workhardplayhard", "i wouldn\u2019t really say i\u2019m a foodie but sometimes i come across a food while travelling that inspires me to talk about it that was the case with the sm\u00f8rrebr\u00f8d an open-faced sandwiches loved by the danes apparently the sm\u00f8rrebr\u00f8d became popular in the 19th century as an cheap and satisfying lunch when factory workers needed to eating their midday meal away from home using a thin slice of dense sourdough rye bread called rugbr\u00f8d as their base workers would piled whatever leftovers they had onto the bread in the hope that the sandwiches would fill them up until dinner eventually what started as a poor man\u2019s invention became a danish gastronomic tradition today danes have certainly perfected the art of the sm\u00f8rrebr\u00f8d there are no ingredients off limits when creating this open-faced sandwich and the main aim seems to be to arrange a complexity of textures and contrasting flavours as artfully as possible on that oh so small slice of rugbr\u00f8d a fantastic interpretation of the sandwich and definitely among the best i\u2019ve ever had sm\u00f8rrebr\u00f8d latergram denmark 2016",
